in Spain; it is found mainly in Mexico and Cuba."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Armager was born about 1441, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Richard Adams about 1459, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1520, at the age of 80."},"et":{"Abt 1441–1520":"umbes 1441–1520","1440–1499":"1440–1499","1460–1544":"1460–1544","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","1463–1534":"1463–1534","1464–Female":"1464–Surnud","1478–1530":"1478–1530","1441–1520":"1441–1520","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","Abt 1499":"umbes 1499","1534":"1534","1478":"1478","1544":"1544","about 1459":"umbes 1459","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","Abt 1441":"umbes 1441","1530":"1530","1464":"1464","1463":"1463","1441":"1441","about 1464":"umbes 1464","about 1460":"umbes 1460","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Burslem, Staffordshire, , England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1441–1520":"noin 1441–1520","1440–1499":"1440–1499","1460–1544":"1460–1544","1460–Female":"1460–Kuollut","1463–1534":"1463–1534","1464–Female":"1464–Kuollut","1478–1530":"1478–1530","1441–1520":"1441–1520","1440":"1440","1460":"1460","Abt 1499":"noin 1499","1534":"1534","1478":"1478","1544":"1544","about 1459":"noin 1459","1499":"1499","1520":"1520","Abt 1441":"noin 1441","1530":"1530","1464":"1464","1463":"1463","1441":"1441","about 1464":"noin 1464","about 1460":"noin 1460","Burslem, Staffordshire, England":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England","Burslem, Staffo